    <fr:p>
      By symmetry, it suffices to prove the claims concerning <fr:tex>i=0</fr:tex>.
      Set <fr:tex>A_0= \bigoplus  A_0^{p,q}</fr:tex> and define filtrations <fr:tex>W</fr:tex> and <fr:tex>F</fr:tex> on <fr:tex>A_0</fr:tex> by the equations of <fr:ref
addr="hodge-theory-ii-1.2.11"
href="hodge-theory-ii-1.2.11.xml"
taxon="Lemma"
number="1.2.11"></fr:ref>.
      The canonical map <fr:tex>i</fr:tex> from <fr:tex>A_0</fr:tex> to <fr:tex>A</fr:tex> is compatible with the filtrations <fr:tex>W</fr:tex> and <fr:tex>F</fr:tex>.
      Furthermore, by <fr:ref
addr="hodge-theory-ii-1.2.8"
href="hodge-theory-ii-1.2.8.xml"
taxon="Lemma"
number="1.2.8"></fr:ref>, <fr:tex>\operatorname {Gr} _W(i)</fr:tex> is an isomorphism, and induces isomorphisms of graded objects

      <fr:tree
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"
toc="true"
numbered="false"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="false"
expanded="true"
root="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>718</fr:anchor><fr:taxon>Equation</fr:taxon><fr:addr>hodge-theory-ii-1.2.11.4</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-ii-1.2.11.4.xml</fr:route><fr:number>1.2.11.4</fr:number><fr:parent>hodge-theory-ii-1.2.11</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:tex
display="block">            \sum _{p+q=n} A_0^{p,q}            \xrightarrow { \sim }   \operatorname {Gr} _W^{-n}(A)           =  \sum _{p+q=n} A^{p,q}.         \tag{1.2.11.4}         </fr:tex></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>

      The morphism <fr:tex>i</fr:tex> is thus an isomorphism, and the <fr:tex>A_0^{p,q}</fr:tex> give a bigrading of <fr:tex>A</fr:tex>.
    </fr:p>

    <fr:p><fr:ref
addr="hodge-theory-ii-1.2.11.1"
href="hodge-theory-ii-1.2.11.1.xml"
taxon="Equation"
number="1.2.11.1"></fr:ref> then says that <fr:tex>\operatorname {Gr} _W(i)</fr:tex> is an isomorphism.
      By <fr:ref
addr="hodge-theory-ii-1.2.11.4"
href="hodge-theory-ii-1.2.11.4.xml"
taxon="Equation"
number="1.2.11.4"></fr:ref>, <fr:tex>\operatorname {Gr} _F \operatorname {Gr} _W(i)</fr:tex> is an isomorphism, and thus so too are <fr:tex>\operatorname {Gr} _W \operatorname {Gr} _F(i)</fr:tex> and <fr:tex>\operatorname {Gr} _F(i)</fr:tex>.
      Equation <fr:ref
addr="hodge-theory-ii-1.2.11.2"
href="hodge-theory-ii-1.2.11.2.xml"
taxon="Equation"
number="1.2.11.2"></fr:ref> then follows.
    </fr:p>
